<TITLE> Minister calls for skilled manpower </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 2 (bdnews24.com)  Jute and textile minister Abdul Latif Siddiquee has asked industrialists to create more skilled manpower for the garment sector. He was speaking at the launch of a four day exhibition of textile and garments machinery at Bangabandhu International Conference Centre. Siddique said Bangladesh not only had to import machinery for the garment sector but also foreign technicians to operate them. "I think we should create skilled manpower." Siddiqui told industrialists: "Work towards creating the man behind the machine. You will have to come forward to create skilled manpower." He assured that the government would help them. "If we can do so, the money spent on foreigners will remain in the country," the minister said. Industries minister Dilip Barua said: "The precondition of local and foreign investment is political stability. The government is determined to maintain the stability." Bangladesh Textile Mills Association president Abdul Hai Sarker urged the government to solve gas crisis for smooth production. "Just when we are about to get over the global downturn, the gas crisis has halted our advancement." He said that the textile manufacturing companies considered Bangladesh a hub in the inudstry. "But this image now hinges upon the availability of gas and power." Sarker said 570 companies from 30 countries are taking part in the fair. The fair will continue until Feb 5. bdne
